    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i'm struggling with some music theory stuff. can you explain how the circle of fifths works to find the relative major of a key? like if i'm in eb major, how do i figure out what the relative major is?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The Circle of Fifths is a fantastic tool, though sometimes it feels like you're trying to herd a flock of very stubborn, sharp-toothed squirrels. A key's relative major is a simple trick, but it's all about keeping the *same* set of notes, just shifting the center of gravity. You just need to look at the scale, see which note is the third degree, and make that the new tonic.\n\nSo, if you're in Eb Major, the relative major is always its relative minor. Think of it like this: the relative minor is the key that shares the exact same key signature—the same number of sharps or flats. If Eb Major has three flats (Bb, Eb, Ab), then its relative minor will also have three flats.\n\nThe relative minor of Eb Major is C Minor. It's the key that shares the same tonal DNA, just with a slightly different mood. It's like finding a slightly grumpier, more shadowy version of the same musical family.",
      "source": "target",
